<div class="section">
    <div class="is-header">
        When to Use
    </div>
    <div class="is-medium-font">
        Buttons can be used in any scenario where you need to trigger an action.  The various types and when to use them is as follows:
        <ul>
            <li>
                Neutral
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        For actions that aren't urgent, simply available.  This helps them stay undistracting.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                Primary
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        For actions that are primary given the current user context.  For instance, the edit button on the inspector.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                Negative
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        For actions that primary but destructive given the current user context.  For instance, the cancel button on the inspector.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                Positive
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        For actions that primary and positive given the current user context.  For instance, the save button on the inspector.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="section">
    <div class="is-header">
        How to Use
    </div>
    <div>
        <div class="is-medium-font">
            <p>This pattern isn't a component, it's just showing how to implement a button.</p>

            <p>A button can consist of both text and an icon, text alone, or an icon alone.</p>
            
            <p>If there is an icon, it should always come on the left.  The reasoning behind this is that the icon should eventually (if not immediately) 
            indicate what the button does.  As such, it should be the first thing the user sees (if they're in a language that reads left to right).</p>

            <p>We have a variable called minimum button size that indicates the minimum size needed to allow a user to accurately
            interact with it.  There are a number of articles and varying opinions on what minium sizes for interactive elements should be 
            (see <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/target-size.html" target="_blank">W3C Target Size</a> for some examples).  Thankfully
            our UI allows a varying number of opinions to reign.  Our theming allows users or admins to adjust spacing (comfortable, cozy, compact).</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>